<BaseLayout title="The &quot;Ishte Saku&quot;/&quot;Bas Itna&quot; Paradox — Grusha G S" description="A product case study on Swiggy Instamart's catalog architecture and what it would take to capture the daily Indian household.">
  <article class="container case-study">

    <div class="case-study-meta">Case Study · March 2026 · Bengaluru</div>

    <h1 class="case-study-title">The "Ishte Saku"/"Bas Itna" Paradox</h1>
    <p class="case-study-subtitle">
      Why Swiggy Instamart is losing the daily Indian household, and what it would take to win it back.
    </p>

    <p>
      In Q3 FY26, Swiggy Instamart delivered 106 million orders to 12.8 million users across 128 cities. The speed has arrived. The selection has arrived. And yet, in the household I grew up in, the kirana store downstairs is still open, still busy, and still serving the same customers it served before any of this existed.
    </p>

    <p>
      This case study is about why.
    </p>

    <h2>Design by accretion</h2>

    <p>
      Swiggy launched Instamart in August 2020, betting that Indian urban households would adopt fifteen-minute grocery delivery the way they had adopted thirty-minute restaurant delivery. The bet paid off on the surface metrics. By Q3 FY26, Instamart was processing 106.4 million orders per quarter from 12.8 million users, generating ₹7,938 crore in gross order value, operating 1,136 dark stores, and growing at 108% year-on-year. The infrastructure is real. The customer base is large. The brand is strong.
    </p>

    <p>
      But the catalog that sits on top of this infrastructure was built on assumptions borrowed from a different shopping culture. Pre-packaged SKUs in fixed sizes. Basket minimums that reward planned, larger orders. A merchandising logic optimized for per-SKU margin and warehouse efficiency. The catalog assumes a user who shops the way urban supermarket customers in the West shop — weekly, in bulk, against a planned list, with the storage to absorb the leftovers.
    </p>

    <p>
      Most Indian middle-class households do not shop that way. They shop in small, unplanned, frequent runs, triggered by immediate need. The unit of purchase is whatever the household actually needs in the next day or two, and it is almost never the unit a category manager somewhere upstream chose to pre-package. The catalog had been designed for a shopper who does not exist in most of the homes the platform claims to serve. And the consequence of that mismatch is now showing up in the company's quarterly filings.
    </p>

    <h2>The challenge</h2>

    <p>
      In Q3 FY26, Instamart lost ₹908 crore. Across the first nine months of FY26, cumulative losses reached ₹2,327 crore against ₹2,802 crore in revenue — losing roughly 83 paise on every rupee earned. The company is not failing on growth. GOV is up 108% year-on-year. The company is failing on unit economics, and the lever it has chosen to fix the unit economics is one I believe is pointed in the wrong direction.
    </p>

    <p>
      Swiggy's response to the profitability gap has been Maxxsaver, a basket-building program designed to encourage users to consolidate purchases into larger, less frequent orders. The strategy is explicit and stated by Swiggy's own leadership. Instamart CEO Amitesh Jha, in a recent earnings call: <em>"We believe that this is the right way to approach both basket building for the end consumer, making sure that they get great offers as well as making sure that they come back to our platform again and again."</em>
    </p>

    <p>
      The bet has worked on the metric Swiggy is tracking. Average order value has risen from approximately ₹420 in FY24 to ₹612 in Q1 FY26 to ₹697 in Q2 FY26 — a 65% increase in eighteen months. Non-grocery items, which carry higher margins, now make up 26% of Instamart's GOV, up from 7% a year earlier. The basket-building strategy is doing what it was designed to do.
    </p>

    <p>
      Losses are still widening.
    </p>

    <p>
      The goal of this case study is to argue that the direction is wrong. The lever Instamart is missing is not basket size. It is frequency. And the reason frequency is stuck is the same reason my mother walks downstairs to the kirana store instead of opening the app: the catalog cannot accept the shape of the small, exact, immediate purchases that would drive the frequency number up.
    </p>

    <p>
      There is a second number from Swiggy's own filings that makes the gap impossible to ignore. The Q2 FY26 shareholder letter states that Instamart's dark stores are running, at the network average level, at 1,025 orders per day per store — while the same stores can operate at 2,000+ orders per day. Swiggy's own leadership is explicit about what this means: <em>"store-additions are neither the primary growth-lever nor a growth-bottleneck for us in the near-term."</em> Translation: the infrastructure is there, the capacity is there, and the company knows it. The question Swiggy is not answering in the letter — and the question this case study is trying to answer — is what the next lever is, given that the store count is not it.
    </p>

