    <h3>My role</h3>

    <p>
      This case study was researched and written by me as a single contributor over the course of two weeks, working alone. I conducted the household observation, the kirana price comparison, the synthesis of existing public research on Swiggy Instamart, and the design of the proposed solutions. There is no team behind this work. There is no internal Swiggy data. Everything in this case study is built from publicly observable evidence, one household's lived experience, one focused round of fieldwork in Bengaluru, and the numbers Swiggy publishes in its own quarterly filings.
    </p>

    <p>
      I am writing this case study as part of a transition from a data science background into product management. The framing of the problem and the diagnostic instinct — looking for what is <em>not</em> in the dashboard rather than what the dashboard says — both come from that background. The product thinking is what I am building, and this case study is one of the early attempts at it.
    </p>

    <h2>Kickoff: starting at home</h2>

    <p>
      I did not begin this work with a research plan or a list of hypotheses. I began it by paying attention to what was happening in my own household, because the user I was most interested in understanding lived in the same house as me, and the easiest way to understand her was to watch.
    </p>

    <p>
      The user, in this case, is my mother. She manages the small purchase decisions for our household in Bengaluru — the daily cardamom for chai, the half-kilo of onions for that night's cooking, the curd that needs to be bought today because it spoils tomorrow. She has been making these decisions for forty years. She does not call it a shopping pattern or a replenishment grammar. She calls it shopping. But when I sat with her and asked her to walk me through what she had been buying, three things became hard to ignore.
    </p>

    <p>
      She bought in quantities Instamart does not sell. She closed the app silently when it could not serve her, without complaining or contacting support. And she relied on the kirana store downstairs not as a backup but as a parallel system, used for a specific class of purchases that Instamart's catalog was never designed to accept.
    </p>

    <p>
      I had assumed, when I started, that the kirana store was Instamart's legacy competitor — slowly being replaced as the app got faster and stocked more items. I do not believe that anymore. After a few days of paying attention, what I saw instead was that the kirana store is a fulfillment partner the household has chosen unilaterally for the kinds of small, exact, immediate purchases the app cannot currently serve. Swiggy is not in the process of winning these purchases. It has already lost them, quietly, in millions of households like mine, and it does not know.
    </p>

    <p>
      This was the beginning of the working hypothesis that became the rest of this case study: that Instamart's catalog is built on a unit of purchase the Indian household does not actually use, and that the cost of this mismatch is invisible in every dashboard the company currently looks at.
    </p>

    <h2>Working backwards from the kirana store</h2>

    <p>
      To test whether the pattern I suspected was real, I needed evidence beyond a conversation. So I did the thing PM work actually requires, which is to stop arguing about the problem in the abstract and go look at it. Over a few days, I documented ten items across both channels — opening Instamart on my phone and walking downstairs to the kirana store with the same item in mind, photographing what I found in each place.
    </p>

    <p>
      The ten items are not a shopping list. They are a sample, chosen to test whether the catalog mismatch generalized across categories. Some of them were things my mother had recently needed. Others were things I picked deliberately because I wanted to see whether the pattern held across very different kinds of products — perishables, dry staples, personal care, festival items, daily-use consumables. If the pattern only showed up in one or two categories, the problem would be a narrow merchandising gap. If it showed up across all of them, the problem would be structural.
    </p>

    <p>
      It showed up across all of them.
    </p>

    <h3>Cardamom (elaichi)</h3>
    <p>
      My mother needed a few pods for evening tea. On Instamart, the smallest size is a 15-gram packet at ₹76. The kirana store sells a small hanging sachet for ₹10. The ratio between what she wanted to spend and what Instamart forced her to spend is 7.6x.
    </p>

