    </figure>

    <h3>Curd (Nandini)</h3>
    <p>
      My mother specifically wanted a 250-gram Nandini packet for the next day's meal. Nandini, the state dairy cooperative, manufactures a 200-gram packet — I photographed the packet itself, with the label reading "Net Quantity: 200g." On Instamart, the smallest Nandini size is 500 grams. The 200-gram packet exists as a physical product, is sold across Bengaluru, and is simply not on Instamart's catalog. This is not a supply chain limitation. It is a merchandising decision.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src="/images/item-curd.png" alt="Side by side comparison of Nandini curd on Instamart (smallest is 500g) and a photograph of the physical Nandini 200g packet with the label reading Net Quantity 200g" />
      <figcaption>Curd: Instamart's smallest Nandini size is 500g. The 200g Nandini packet exists as a real manufactured product — the label reads "Net Quantity: 200g" — but it is not on the catalog.</figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      Ten items, two channels, one pattern. In every case, the kirana store offers a unit of purchase that matches what a household actually needs, and Instamart offers a larger minimum that the user must either accept or abandon. Across the ten items, the kirana store wins nine of them and Instamart wins one — and even the one Instamart wins involves the user buying more than they needed.
    </p>

    <h2>Reframing the problem</h2>

    <p>
      Looking at the ten items together, three distinct failure modes show up. Each one calls for a different kind of product intervention.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Pack size mismatch.</strong> The user needs a quantity that does not match any pre-packaged size Instamart lists. The Nandini 200-gram packet is the cleanest example — it exists as a real product but is not on the catalog. This is a merchandising decision, not a supply problem.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Variable quantity gap.</strong> For items like atta, sugar, onions, and loose vegetables, the natural unit at a kirana store is whatever the customer asks for. The shopkeeper weighs it out. There is no fixed SKU at all. Instamart cannot replicate this with a better list of SKUs — you cannot list every possible weight in 50-gram increments. The only way to serve this is to let the user specify the quantity as input and have the system translate it.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Search intent gap.</strong> When a user searches for "shampoo sachet" or "coffee sachet" on Instamart, the platform does not recognize "sachet" as a meaningful category. It returns bulk sizes and autocorrects the query. Even if Instamart stocked sachets tomorrow, users searching for them might not find them, because the search layer does not have the mental model.
    </p>

